indicators.title: Number of improved rice varieties released
indicators.description: Maize varieties that have undergone independent external evaluation (i.e. tests for distinctiveness, uniformity and stability as well as the value for cultivation and use) leading to its registration by the National Variety Release Committee. The registration establishes legal ownership of the new variety.

indicators.title: Number of improved agronomic practices developed and formally recommended to the national extension services
indicators.description:
Agronomic practice: Application of a distinct management approach / innovation to enhance crop production (e.g. green manure use, fertilizer application rates, Conservation Agriculture, Water management). Agronomic practices are steps farmers incorporate into their farm management systems to improve soil quality, enhance water use, manage crop residue, and improve the environment through better fertilizer management.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National Agricultural Research and Extension Services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of improved pest management practices developed and formally recommended to national extension services.
indicators.description:
“Improved pest management” refers to new methods and approaches for prevention and treatment of pests.
“Pests” are organisms that damage or interfere with desirable crop plants in the fields and orchards, landscapes, or wild lands, or other structures. A pest can be a plant (weed), vertebrate (bird, rodent, or other mammal), invertebrate (insect, mite, or snail) and nematode.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of improved disease management practices developed and formally recommended to national extension services.
indicators.description:
“Improved disease management practices” refer to new methods and approaches for prevention and treatment of diseases.
A “disease” is a pathogen (bacteria, virus, or fungus) infecting a plant and thereby damaging or interfering with the desirable crop growth in the fields and orchards.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services(NARES)

indicators.title: Number of improved water management practices developed and recommended to the national extension services (e.g. moisture conservation technics, irrigation scheduling , irrigation methods)
indicators.description:
“Improved water management practices” refer to efficient use of water for enhanced crop production (e.g. moisture conservation technics, irrigation scheduling, and irrigation methods). Efficient water use implies use of agricultural water saving techniques such as varieties / soil management techniques.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services(NARES)

indicators.title: Number of improved postharvest storage technologies developed and formally recommended to the national advisory service (e.g. post harvest storage facilities, pest management)
indicators.description:
“Improved postharvest storage technologies” are innovations/methods that help to keep harvested produce at a quality level that is adequate for consumption, marketing and processing (e.g. post-harvest storage facilities, pest management).
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and Extension Services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of improved processing technologies developed and formally recommended to the national advisory service
indicators.description:
Innovations/procedures for modifying /transforming/ value adding to agricultural produce to prolong shelf life, improve quality, availability for income generation.
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and extension services(NARES)

indicators.title: Number of labour saving technologies developed and formally recommended to the national extension services
indicators.description:
Innovations/practices aiming at reducing the manpower/drudgery, reducing cost of production / processing for the agricultural output (e.g., crop, dairy).
Note: “formally recommended“: Formal publication of a production guide/manual by the National 
Agricultural Research and extension services (NARES).

indicators.title: Number of trial sites established
indicators.description: A trial site is an area that has been selected for the purposes of carrying out a research trial/experiment funded by APPSA. These trial sites include the conservation sites. This indicator will measure the total number of trial sites in all the R & D projects established by RCoL per year.

indicators.title: Number of demonstrations established
indicators.description: A demonstration is a platform where technologies (varieties and management practices) are established to create awareness to stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of farmers participating in on-farm participatory research
indicators.description: Farmers taking part in agricultural research trials in close collaboration with APPSA funded R&D projects per country.

indicators.title: Number of field days conducted
indicators.description: A field day is platform where technologies are showcased for purposes of creating awareness to the stakeholders, getting feedback and sharing lessons learnt.

indicators.title: Number of farmers participating in field days (by gender)
indicators.description:
Farmers attending field days facilitated by R&D project where technologies are showcased for learning purposes.
Note: A “farmer” is an individual involved in crop and animal production for food, income or raw materials.

indicators.title: Number of fairs held to show case technologies
indicators.description: A fair is a forum for displaying agricultural technologies with the purpose of creating awareness to the stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of participants attending fairs
Number of extension personnel trained
indicators.description:
An extension personnel is an individual involved in facilitation of agriculture technology transfer 
Capacity strengthening of advisory service providers and lead farmers is another approach for technology dissemination.

indicators.title: Number of lead farmers trained
indicators.description:
Lead farmers trained in APPSA promoted technologies by the RCoL.
“Lead farmers” represent the group of innovative and successful farmers within the local community who are committed to training their fellow farmers on agriculture methods and technologies. Typically, they are selected by the community and registered as lead farmers with the field extension office in a given administrative unit (e.g. district, EPA, block, camp). They are in direct contact with researcher or extension personnel to help champion the demonstration of a technology in their areas.

indicators.title: Number of IEC materials published
indicators.description: Information Education Communication (IEC) materials include brochures, success stories, pamphlets, briefs, extension manuals, flyers, posters, fact sheets and bulletins. The indicator describes IEC materials developed and published by RCoL.

indicators.title: Number of IEC materials distributed
indicators.description: IEC materials include brochures, success stories, pamphlets, briefs, extension manuals, flyers, posters, fact sheets and bulletins printed and distributed by RCoL. The indicator describes Information Education Communication (IEC) materials printed and distributed or shared electronically by RCoL to stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of sms messages dispatched to lead farmers on promoted technologies
indicators.description: Number of messages (content) dispatched to lead farmers on promoted technologies by the RCoL. The messages can be in different languages.

indicators.title: Number of sms responses by lead farmers
indicators.description: Total number/percentage of responses by lead farmers made to the RCoL.

indicators.title: Number of TV documentaries produced and aired
indicators.description: TV documentaries sponsored by APPSA to reach the target population with a message on a specific technology or practice.

indicators.title: Number of radio programs produced and aired
indicators.description: Radio programs sponsored by APPSA to reach the target population with a message on a specific technology.

indicators.title: Quantity of breeder seed produced
indicators.description: Breeder Seed is produced under direct supervision of the plant breeder and represents the true pedigree of the variety. Normally available in small quantities (Kgs), and is planted to produce foundation/basic seed.

indicators.title: Quantity of foundation/basic seed produced
indicators.description: Foundation/basic Seed is the first generation of seed multiplication using the breeder seed. It is produced under direct control of a seed quality and certification unit or a similar formal entity. It is available in limited quantities, (Kgs) and is planted to produce certified seed.

indicators.title: Quantity of certified seeds produced
indicators.description: Certified Seed is produced from foundation/basic seed. It is available in large quantities (tons), and is sold to farmers for general grain production. Typically it is produced by seed companies, directly or under contract farming.

indicators.title: Number of improved varieties released by the RCoL that can be accessed by farmers
indicators.description:
Certified crop seed varieties that are registered under ZARI/IIAM/DARS and were either generated or disseminated with the help of APPSA research funds.  An improved variety is deemed accessible to farmers if it is available to 40% of the marketing outlets in the target districts
Note: “Accessed by farmers“ means that it can be acquired or purchased on the local market (e.g. stocked with agro dealers, government subsidized inputs)

indicators.title: Number of technologies released by a RCoL in two countries and that can be  accessed by Farmers
indicators.description:
Certified seed varieties, agronomic and postharvest practices that are registered in two APPSA program countries under the name of one of the three institutions ZARI/IIAM/DARS, and which were either generated or disseminated with the help of APPSA research funds.
Note: “accessed by farmers” means that it can be acquired or purchased on the local market (e.g. stocked with agro dealers, government subsided inputs).
